      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Europium is a grey-coloured, soft and shiny metal. It is a member of the lanthanide series; chemically reactive. In air it oxidises to europium(III) oxide E</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">u</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. At elevated temperatures it reacts with water to produce europium(III) hydroxide, </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Eu(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Europium also reacts with acids to form salts, for example europium(III) chloride -</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> EuC</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">l</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. Europium was discovered and obtained in 1901 by a French chemist Eugene Anatole Demarcay. It was named after Europe.</text>
